We're approaching a point where social media platforms are populated almost entirely by influencers. The paradox? There's hardly anyone left to influence. Influencers are followed by thousands of smaller influencers, who in turn are trailed by countless micro-influencers.
It's a wild situation.
Traditionally, influencing was about sharing narratives, opinions, or products [ https://substack.com/redirect/b1e681d8-c117-4c37-bde8-34eec4ec08e9?j=eyJ1IjoiNHFkNTF0In0.3VeGxV4zk4PWCIHpd0Onx-O6RwY6Z7JeNCNSiNEVLgU ] with a wide audience. But the modern influencer often aims to remain unaffected by others. This creates a strange dynamic: many followers aren't genuinely interested in the content anymore. Instead, they follow accounts with larger reach hoping to capture a bit of that audience for themselves.
They comment on videos or threads, not out of genuine engagement, but to entice people to click on their profiles and gain followers.
Social media has shifted focus to engagement tactics and algorithm hacks. Clickbait and attention-grabbing tricks have become more important than quality content.
In 2024, the average human attention span might be shorter than that of a goldfish—less than eight seconds.
Everyone is vying for your attention.
Influencers of all sizes share a common goal:
Sliding into DMs and Climbing Ladders
That's why influencers often reach out privately to others at a similar level, trying to build connections. While some interactions are sincere, many operate on the principle of reciprocity. If I'm friendly in your DMs, you're more likely to like or repost my content. It's just how we're wired.
It's partly about forming human connections and partly about playing the algorithm. But let's face it—the main objective for everyone on social media is to have more followers than the next person.
To expand their reach.
Those friendly DMs aren't necessarily from real friends. And this problem extends beyond social media into society at large.
Meanwhile, in China...
These days, it seems everyone wants to be an influencer. A 2019 Harris Poll survey reported by Bloomberg [ https://substack.com/redirect/4c199ad3-3024-47b3-af6e-82ce4ecf0402?j=eyJ1IjoiNHFkNTF0In0.3VeGxV4zk4PWCIHpd0Onx-O6RwY6Z7JeNCNSiNEVLgU ] found that 30% of American kids aspire to be YouTubers. Meanwhile, 60% of Chinese children dream of becoming astronauts, with less than 20% seeking social media fame.
In our increasingly noisy world, those who shout the loudest gain a slight advantage. People are frantically focusing on personal branding because social media platforms have steered us to believe it's the only way to stay relevant.
Just being good at your craft isn't enough anymore. You need to be a brand and make sure people know your name.
This race for follower counts is overtaking the pursuit of quality. It's why we see posts like:
The new [insert name] AI is going to change everything and you are so not ready. Here's how to use it to win:
– A thread (1/37)
Algorithm Gymnastics and the Race to the Bottom
We're trapped in a hamster wheel, scrambling for attention in the hope that someone like Elon Musk might retweet our meme, earning us 10,000 new followers.
We've moved past having something meaningful to say—unless it's trolling online to stir up controversy. And if someone wants to hedge their bets, they'll start a post with "Unpopular opinion:" even when the sentiment is widely shared.
Everyone is desperately trying to "game the algorithm" to slightly increase their share of the spotlight. What they fail to see is how meaningless those numbers really are.
The Hollow Pursuit of Vanity Metrics
Years ago, I noticed many "popular" Instagram accounts in my niche believed you needed to buy your first 100,000 followers. We ended up with profiles boasting 250,000 followers but getting only 90 likes on a post.
Who are they really fooling?
Many of your followers aren't truly friends. They're using you as a ladder or a trampoline to propel their own success. They're not interested in what you say or stand for.
It's pure self-interest.
When one of your posts does well, they'll try to imitate it next time. If it doesn't get much engagement, they make a mental note to avoid that approach.
What they don't realize is that their followers are doing the same thing. Those audiences don't care about the content either; they're just aiming to reach their next follower milestone.
A thousand followers? Ten thousand? A hundred thousand?
The (Slow) Return to Substance
Today's influencers are heavily invested in short-form content. Quick, 15-second vertical videos with flashy, bouncing subtitles and rapid background changes every few seconds to keep viewers hooked.
This editing style rose to prominence with Mr. Beast (Jimmy Donaldson) and has become a template for chasing engagement across all social media platforms—not just YouTube. The problem is that each new wave of influencers puts less time, effort, and substance into their work. They're just copying Donaldson's editing tricks.
Most of the online community is caught in this ultra-fast loop, scrambling for engagement in any way possible.
Breaking the Cycle
As with any trend, there's a group that gets tired of it quickly. Some people genuinely want to gain value from their online activities. Others might do it to feel superior to those with a "four-second attention span." Whatever the motivation, long-form content with real substance is slowly making a return.
Your personal brand shouldn't be about gaming the algorithm. It should be about showcasing the quality of what you do. And sometimes, that approach attracts followers and high-paying sponsors [ https://substack.com/redirect/c43c1fb5-b3ed-4521-9600-de8c0d2f280d?j=eyJ1IjoiNHFkNTF0In0.3VeGxV4zk4PWCIHpd0Onx-O6RwY6Z7JeNCNSiNEVLgU ].
This shift needs to happen, or we'll remain stuck in this endless cycle.
Change is occurring, though—albeit slowly.
We're not there yet, but from my own experience, a single follower who reads this entire 1,000-word article is far more valuable than a thousand followers gained from a quick 15-second video.
